dataIdInfo.idPurp: The Big Thicket National Preserve (BITH) vegetation inventory project was initiated by the National Park Service (NPS) Vegetation Mapping Inventory (VMI) Program. The goals of the vegetation mapping project were to adequately classify, describe, and map vegetation types of BITH and provide resource managers, biological researchers, and the NPS Natural Resource Inventory and Monitoring (I&M) Program with useful baseline vegetation information. This vegetation information is to support a wide variety of resource assessment, park management, and planning needs, providing a structure for framing and answering critical scientific questions about vegetation communities and their relation to environmental processes across the landscape.
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
The NPS VMI Program is an effort to classify, describe, and map existing vegetation of national park units for the NPS Natural Resource I&M Program. The NPS VMI Program is managed by the NPS I&M Division and provides baseline vegetation information to the NPS Natural Resource I&M Program. The geographic information system (GIS) format spatial data set of vegetation for BITH was created for the NPS VMI Program.

The BITH project boundary covers an area of approximately 45,441.8 ha (113,104.6 ac). Vegetation communities at BITH were classified and mapped by Colorado State University (CSU) under a cooperative agreement with the NPS VMI Program. CSU Mappers, ecologists, and botanists collaborated to affirm vegetation types within the U.S. National Vegetation Classification (USNVC) at BITH and to determine how best to map them by using aerial imagery. To map the vegetation and land cover at BITH, 51 map classes were developed. Of these 51 map classes, 46 represent natural (including ruderal) vegetation types, most of which types are recognized within the USNVC. The remaining five map classes represented non-USNVC land use cover classes (agriculture, non-vegetated barren land or borrow pit, developed open space, developed low, medium, or high intensity, and water). Features were interpreted from digital aerial imagery using a heads-up digitizing approach in geographic information systems. The map classification scheme used to create the vegetation data set is designed to represent local vegetation types at the finest level possible using the National Vegetation Classification Standard (NVCS) Version 2. A minimum mapping unit of 0.5 hectares was used for all communities. Physiognomic information was also recorded. The final BITH vegetation map consists of 7,271 polygons totaling 45,771.8 ha (113,104.6 ac). Mean polygon size is 6.3 ha (15.6 ac). Of the total area, 43,314.4 ha (106,310.1 ac) or 94.0% represent natural or ruderal vegetation map classes. Aerial Imagery that was used includes 2014 Hexagon Imagery, 2016 and 2018 USDA-FSA NAIP imagery, and 2015 leaf-off imagery from the TNRIS TOP. In addition to using aerial imagery, 2017 Neches River Topographic / Bathymetric LiDAR data available from the USGS was used to analyze vegetation structure at BITH. The NVCS standard was applied and a list of vegetation associations present was documented and compiled. The database includes tables documenting the USNVC hierarchy and allows for spatial queries that show different levels of the USNVC hierarchy associated with a vegetation polygon.

Accuracy Assessment (AA) data were collected from a total of 784 randomly allocated AA sample points in the summer of 2019. The overall accuracy of the aggregated BITH map was 92.1%. Accuracies associated with individual map classes are presented in the final project report.

The BITH vegetation inventory project delivers many geospatial and vegetation data products. These products consist of an in-depth project report discussing methods and results, which include descriptions and a field key to vegetation associations, map classification and map-class descriptions, and a contingency table listing AA results. The suite of products also includes a database of vegetation plots, verification sites, and AA sites; digital pictures of field sites; field data sheets; digital aerial imagery; digital maps; and a geodatabase of vegetation and land cover (map layer), field sites (vegetation plots, verification sites, and AA sites), aerial imagery index, project boundary, and metadata. All geospatial products are projected in Universal Transverse Mercator, Zone 15 North, by using the North American Datum of 1983.

The citation for the projects report is:

Ley, M., T. Baldvins, H. Pilkington, D. Jones and K. Anderson. 2021. Vegetation classification and mapping project: Big Thicket National Preserve. Natural Resource Report NPS/XXXX/NRR—2021/XXXX. National Park Service, Fort Collins, Colorado.

report.measDesc:
Topology validated using the bith_vegpoly_Topology, errors corrected, and exceptions marked using the ArcGIS Error Inspector.
Additionally, this feature class is related to the tbl_vegpoly_nlcd2001, tbl_vegpoly_nvcs2_cultural, and tbl_vegpoly_nvcs2_natural business tables through the vegpoly_nlcd2001, vegpoly_nvcs2_cultural, and vegpoly_nvcs2_natural relationship classes. They all use a one-to-many relationship.

dataSource.srcDesc: Imagery used to digitize features at a 1:800 to 1:1,500 scale.

srcExt.exDesc: Date pertains to when the images were taken. All images taken during 2014.

dataSource.srcDesc: The U.S. National Vegetation Classification (USNVC) system was used to determine the community name and description. Version 2.03 (March 2019) was used.

srcExt.exDesc: Database accessed between May 2, 2016 and March 31, 2021.

prcStep.stepDesc: Vegetation polygons were digitized on-screen using aerial imagery. Based on field survey results, each vegetation polygon was classified to a map class associated with the lowest level of the USNVC classification. In some situations in which an USNVC classification was not present, an installation special association was created by the vegetation mapping specialist. See final report for details on field methods.
